04816nam a22007695i 9780520972964DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019020845  a97805209729647 a10.1525/97805209729642doi  a(DE-B1597)563084  a(OCoLC)1163877851  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aBS1199.D34 7aREL1140002bisacsh1 aDoerfler, Maria E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJephthah's Daughter, Sarah's Son :bThe Death of Children in Late Antiquity /cMaria E. Doerfler. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aChristianity in Late Antiquity ;v800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t(Premature) Death as a Good. An Introduction -- t1. Children's Deaths in Late Antiquity in Ritual and Historical Perspective -- t2. East of Eden -- t3. Mourning Sarah's Son -- t4. Echoes of the Akedah -- t5. Death, Demons, and Disaster -- t6. Children and the Sword -- tConclusion. Children in the Quicksand -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLate antiquity was a perilous time for children, who were often the first victims of economic crisis, war, and disease. They had a one in three chance of dying before their first birthday, with as many as half dying before age ten. Christian writers accordingly sought to speak to the experience of bereavement and to provide cultural scripts for parents who had lost a child. These late ancient writers turned to characters like Eve and Sarah, Job and Jephthah as models for grieving and for confronting or submitting to the divine. Jephthah's Daughter, Sarah's Son traces the stories these writers crafted and the ways in which they shaped the lived experience of familial bereavement in ancient Christianity. A compelling social history that conveys the emotional lives of people in the late ancient world, Jephthah's Daughter, Sarah's Son is a powerful portrait of mourning that extends beyond antiquity to the present day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aChildrenxDeathxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 0aParental griefxReligious aspectsxChristianityxHistoryyEarly church, ca. 30-600. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  achildrens death and parental grief.  acompelling.  adying before first birthday.  afamilial bereavement in ancient christianity.  afirst victims of disease.  afirst victims of economic crisis.  afirst victims of war.  ahalf dying before age ten.  alate antiquity.  aperilous time for children.  aportrait of mourning.  apowerful.  asocial history of mourning.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520972964zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520972964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520972964.jpg  a978-3-11-069041-5  UC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070477-8  EBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishb2020